    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Review generation</strong> is the systematic process by which businesses proactively request, collect, and manage customer reviews across platforms like Google Business Profile, Yelp, Trustpilot, and industry-specific directories. Unlike passive review accumulation, review generation uses timing, channel selection, and messaging to increase the volume, velocity, and recency of authentic customer feedback at scale.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Review Acquisition</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Customers who are happy rarely leave reviews unprompted. Customers who are angry often do. Without a review generation strategy, your online reputation is written by your unhappiest customers — not your best ones. That's why systematic review generation is essential for any business that relies on local search visibility, online trust, or social proof to convert prospects.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is review generation?</h2>
        <p>Review generation is the practice of actively asking customers to leave reviews on specified platforms after a positive interaction. It transforms organic, sporadic feedback into a consistent stream of authentic reviews that build trust, improve local rankings, and influence purchasing decisions.</p>
        <p>The three core elements of review generation are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Timing</strong> — requesting reviews at the moment of peak customer satisfaction (post-purchase, post-service, post-milestone)</li>
          <li><strong>Channel</strong> — using SMS, email, in-person requests, or QR codes depending on where your customers are most responsive</li>
          <li><strong>Destination</strong> — directing customers to the most strategically valuable platform (usually Google first)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why review generation matters</h2>
        <p>Reviews influence three distinct business outcomes simultaneously:</p>

        <h3>1. Local SEO rankings</h3>
        <p>Google's local ranking algorithm weighs review signals including total review count, average star rating, review velocity (how frequently new reviews arrive), and the presence of keyword-relevant content in review text. Businesses with consistent, recent reviews from real customers consistently outrank those with sparse or stale review profiles in the local pack.</p>

        <h3>2. Conversion rates</h3>
        <p>Research from BrightLocal shows that 87% of consumers read online reviews for local businesses, and 79% trust online reviews as much as personal recommendations. A business profile moving from 3.5 to 4.3 stars can see a 25-30% increase in click-through from local search results. Reviews are one of the highest-leverage conversion rate optimisation tools available — and they're free.</p>

        <h3>3. Brand trust signals</h3>
        <p>For new visitors unfamiliar with your brand, reviews are the primary trust signal before a purchase decision. A business with 200 reviews and a 4.6 star average signals established quality and reliable service. A business with 12 reviews and a 3.8 average signals uncertainty. The difference in conversion rate between those profiles is often dramatic.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Review velocity matters more than total count</div>
          <p>Google's algorithm values review recency heavily. 50 reviews from this year outranks 500 reviews from 4 years ago. Consistent monthly review generation — even 5-10 new reviews per month — maintains ranking strength. Campaigns that generate 100 reviews in a week then stop are less durable than steady ongoing programmes.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="platforms">Which platforms to prioritise</h2>
        <p>Not all review platforms have equal SEO or conversion value. Prioritise by impact:</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
