                <td>Secondary</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-to-ask">How to ask for reviews effectively</h2>
        <p>The ask is everything. The right request at the right moment dramatically increases response rates compared to a generic "please review us" footer link.</p>

        <h3>SMS requests (highest open rate)</h3>
        <p>Text messages have a 98% open rate vs 20-30% for email. A concise SMS sent within 24 hours of service completion is the highest-converting review request channel for local businesses. Keep it short, personal, and include a direct link to your Google review form.</p>

        <h3>Email follow-ups</h3>
        <p>For e-commerce and SaaS, email sequences work well. Send the first request 24-72 hours post-purchase or post-onboarding. Use a subject line that references the specific product or service. Include one clear CTA — a single link to one review platform. Don't split attention across multiple platforms in one email.</p>

        <h3>In-person and QR code requests</h3>
        <p>For restaurants, salons, and service businesses, a laminated card on the table or counter with a QR code linking directly to the Google review form is effective and frictionless. Train staff to mention it naturally at the moment of settlement or completion.</p>

        <h3>Post-project or milestone requests</h3>
        <p>For service businesses with longer engagement cycles (agencies, consultants, contractors), the optimal ask comes at project completion or a significant milestone. This is when satisfaction peaks and the customer has the most to say.</p>

        <h2 id="policy-compliance">Review policy compliance</h2>
        <p>Every major review platform has policies governing how businesses can solicit reviews. Violations can result in review removals or account penalties.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Google</strong> — permits asking all customers for honest reviews. Prohibits review gating, incentivised reviews, and fake reviews. Prohibits discouraging negative reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Yelp</strong> — most restrictive. Prohibits soliciting reviews in any form. Yelp's algorithm detects and filters reviews it suspects were solicited.</li>
          <li><strong>Trustpilot</strong> — allows inviting customers via their verified review invitation system. Prohibits incentivised or selective invitations.</li>
          <li><strong>FTC (US)</strong> — any business incentivising reviews must disclose the relationship. Undisclosed paid or incentivised reviews violate FTC endorsement guidelines.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The safe universal rule: ask all customers (not just happy ones), ask for honest feedback, and never offer incentives for reviews on any platform.</p>

        <h2 id="responding">Responding to reviews</h2>
        <p>Review generation without response management is incomplete. Google rewards businesses that respond to reviews — it signals an active, engaged business and improves local ranking signals.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Positive reviews</strong> — respond to thank the customer, mention a specific detail they raised, and reinforce the brand voice. Don't use canned responses — they read as automated and undermine trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Negative reviews</strong> — respond within 24-48 hours. Acknowledge the issue, apologise without being defensive, and offer to resolve it privately. Future readers of a negative review are often more influenced by how you respond than by the review itself.</li>
          <li><strong>Neutral reviews</strong> — thank the customer, address any issues raised, and ask what you could do better.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for review generation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Automate the ask.</strong> Manual review requests are inconsistent. Use your CRM, email platform, or a dedicated review management tool to trigger requests automatically after a defined event (purchase, service completion, NPS survey response).</li>
          <li><strong>Link directly to the review form.</strong> Every extra click loses participants. For Google, use your Google Review shortlink — it opens the review form directly on mobile.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask at the right moment.</strong> Peak satisfaction triggers peak response. Map your customer journey and identify the moments of highest delight — that's when to ask.</li>
          <li><strong>Personalise the request.</strong> "Hi [name], we hope you enjoyed [specific service]" converts far better than generic copy. Even a first-name personalisation lifts response rates significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Follow up once.</strong> A single reminder 3-5 days after the initial request is appropriate. Multiple follow-ups feel spammy and damage the customer relationship.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Especially negative ones. The response is as much for future readers as for the reviewer.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor review velocity.</strong> If review volume drops, investigate why — it might signal a customer satisfaction issue, not just a process gap.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common review generation mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Review gating</strong> — only asking happy customers, which violates platform policies and creates a distorted rating</li>
          <li><strong>Asking on Yelp</strong> — Yelp prohibits soliciting reviews; doing so can get reviews filtered</li>
          <li><strong>Sending customers to too many platforms at once</strong> — split attention reduces completion on all platforms; start with one (Google)</li>
          <li><strong>Using generic messaging</strong> — "Please leave us a review" is the lowest-converting possible ask</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews</strong> — leaving negative reviews unanswered signals poor customer service to future readers</li>
          <li><strong>Campaign-style review generation</strong> — generating 100 reviews in a week then stopping looks unnatural and may trigger spam filters</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
